node.text:
That’s a wrap on the 2020/21 season and 174 days of operations! While many things looked different this winter, we are incredibly grateful to have been open for nearly 6 months of skiing and riding—especially given the uncertainty we faced at the start of the season. We truly appreciate the resiliency of our employees, skiers & riders, and the Tahoe community as you adapted with us to make it all possible. THANK YOU.
 
We can’t wait to welcome you all back next season for another winter of skiing & riding, and with a new name for these mountains we call home.

🎥: @whiteroomfilms

node.title: Thank you for making the 2020/21 season happen!

node.text: With tremendous love for both snow and water, @chuckpatterson takes full advantage of his California roots. Growing up skiing the steeps of Squaw Valley led to his love of surfing. Now his passion for waves compliments how Chuck charges the mountains. Since this video was filmed (pre-Covid) Chuck has even brought both sports together by "wave skiing" the infamous Mavericks surf spot. Shot by @whiteroomfilms & @ben_arnst #skicalifornia

node.title: Untracked  Sea & Snow with Chuck Patterson

node.text: Here’s to a community borne from mountains. Because, while seasons change, the mountains always endure. From big city or small, snowy town – we’re all skiers and riders. And, when we stand together, we’re as tall as the mountains. #WeAreTheMTNS. 💙⛰️💛 With gratitude for this amazing community, @IkonPass doubled renewal discounts for 20/21, and extended all savings until May 27. Together, we will endure.

node.text:
The name of the mountain is changing, but the unwavering passion for skiing and riding lives on. As we move into the next chapter here, we’ll be sharing stories of the people who have forever left their mark.

Like Natalie Snider and Susan Chappell Standteiner, pictured here. These ladies and their iconic images epitomize the 1980s skinny ski scene. They mastered the art of letting their hair down, sending off cornices, and ripping through moguls on the mostly un-groomed mountain during that time. Their flair lives on in the historic collection of photographer Larry Prosor and continues to enchant and inspire the next generation of legends today. Read the full story on Natalie and Susan told by Amie Engerbretson in our latest blog. [link in bio]

We want to hear your stories too! Share your own bits of mountain history in the making with #legendsoftahoe for a chance to be featured.

The @u.s.forestservice issued a closure of 9 Northern California National Forests, including the Tahoe National Forest and the Lake Tahoe Basin Management Unit, due to wildfire threat in the region. The order extends from August 22 through September 6 and affects some trails at our mountains. At Squaw Valley, the Shirley Canyon Trail and Granite Chief Trail are closed. The Western States Trail can be accessed via the Thunder Mountain Trail out of the base area, but not by points east. At Alpine Meadows, all forested areas are within the National Forest lands, so access is currently prohibited. This includes the Five Lakes Trail.

The Village, Aerial Tram, activities, and other hiking trails on Squaw Valley private lands will remain open, conditions permitting.

These temporary closures were issued to ensure public and firefighter safety, as well as reduce the potential for new wildfire starts. Please respect all area closures, obey posted signs and closure barriers, and do your part to stay fire safe. The air quality in the North Lake Tahoe area is currently poor, but it can fluctuate based on winds and other factors. We recommend checking our webcams and PurpleAir.com for real-time Air Quality Index (AQI) readings before visiting.

Thank you to the many fire crews and first responders who are working tirelessly to fight wildfires across California. We are incredibly grateful 🙏.

Thank you for sharing your ideas and showing the love for this lift! We received over 1,200 submissions to rename the “Squaw Creek” chairlift. Now that we've narrowed it down to our 6 favorites, it's time to vote. Hit the link in our bio and rank the finalists from your most (1) to least (6) favorite. Voting will be open through August 25.
 
As part of the rename process, we will also be renaming the “Squaw One” chairlift. We are working with members of the Washoe Tribe and plan to rename the chair with their input.

Stay tuned for our overall resort name change announcement in early Fall.

Join Darrel Cruz, Director of the Tribal Historic Preservation Office and Cultural Resources Office of the Washoe Tribe, at High Camp on July 12 and August 9 for a Washoe Cultural Tour. Darrel will share stories of natural landmarks, local plants and animals, Washoe history and culture, and the origins of the name of the Valley. This guided talk is a chance to immerse yourself in the history of the valley & surrounding mountains and view artifacts that show the Washoe way of life that Tribe members seek to preserve today.
 
This event is free, but does not include Aerial Tram access. Bring your 2021/22 Ikon Pass or purchase a special $19 Tram ticket when you register. Ticket sales collected from the event will be donated to the Washoe Cultural Fund. Space is limited, so advanced registration is highly encouraged! Click the link in our bio to reserve your spot.
